Chelsea's midfield has looked tired at times this season, and Mourinho is looking to add some fresh talent to the team.</s>

Tom Ballard, a skilled climber, plans to climb K2, the second highest mountain in the world, 20 years after his mother, Alison Hargreaves, died attempting the same feat. Alison Hargreaves, a renowned climber, was swept to her death in 1995 while descending K2 in 260mph winds. Tom was only six years old at the time. Despite the risks, Tom plans to follow in his mother's footsteps and climb K2. He believes it is his destiny to do so.</s>

UK Oil & Gas Investments claims to have discovered 100 billion barrels of oil in the Weald Basin, an area across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire, and Kent. The company believes this could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. However, industry experts remain skeptical, and one described the claims as "overly optimistic." The site at Horse Hill is believed to have the potential for "significant daily oil production." The oil is thought to be accessible, but fracking may be required to retrieve it. The discovery could create "many thousands" of jobs. The UK government owns the land under the homes in the area, meaning homeowners would not receive any profits from the oil found beneath them. The government would receive taxes on the oil extracted and may receive compensation from the oil company if they base their drilling site on the land.</s>

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA concluded that the first two years of culling had not demonstrated conclusively that ‘controlled shooting’ of free-running badgers could be effective and humane. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. The Environment Secretary promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but said the BVA’s ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting was ‘regrettable’. The Government's strategy includes cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife. The chief vet admitted the benefits of the cull might not be realised in Gloucestershire due to extensive unlawful protest and intimidation by anti-cull campaigners.</s>

The article discusses how modern technology can create problems in budding relationships. It mentions how social media and smartphones can cause issues such as checking phone constantly, taking photos of food, and comparing notes with friends instead of focusing on the date. The article suggests ways to avoid these pitfalls, such as keeping phones off the dining table, not changing relationship status on social media, and not bragging about Tinder matches. It also advises against using technology to record the date or to immediately change relationship status on social media.</s>

Tottenham Hotspur will be without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris for their home clash against Aston Villa on Saturday, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt due to a virus. Provisional squad: Vorm, Friedel, Yedlin, Chiriches, Kaboul, Dier, Vertonghen, Rose, Davies, Bentaleb, Paulinho, Mason, Stambouli, Dembele, Eriksen, Townsend, Lamela, Chadli, Kane, Adebayor, Soldado. Aston Villa boss Tim Sherwood will be without Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, Carles Gil, and Aly Cissokho, but Aly could return after training this week. Provisional squad: Guzan, Given, Lowton, Bacuna, Vlaar, Clark, Baker, Senderos, Okore, Cissokho, Richardson, Delph, Sanchez, Cleverley, Grealish, Cole, N'Zogbia, Benteke, Agbonlahor, Weimann. Kick-off is at 3pm and Tottenham are the favorites to win at 4/7, while the draw is at 14/5 and Aston Villa are at 5/1. Referee is Lee Probert. Tottenham have won their last five PL meetings with Aston Villa, netting two or more goals in each game. Aston Villa have scored just six goals in their last 12 Premier League matches against Tottenham and never more than once in a game. Tottenham have gained 10 points from losing positions at home this season, more than any other side. Aston Villa have gained no points from losing positions away from home in the Premier League this season – the only team not to do so. White Hart Lane is the highest scoring stadium in the Premier League this season (51 goals). Aston Villa haven't won at Tottenham since 2008 when Ashley Young scored the winner in a 2-1 victory. White Hart Lane has also seen the most first half goals this season (27). Christian Benteke has scored seven goals in his last five Premier League appearances. Under Tim Sherwood, Benteke has scored at a rate of one goal every 87 minutes in the Premier League

A mother who made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby at just 20 weeks had her wedding dress redesigned so her tiny daughter could be buried in it. Jaye Cox and her husband, Matthew, decided to deliver their daughter Annabelle prematurely on May 5 last year after scans showed she had developed a serious form of Spina Bifida. Annabelle was born weighing just 290 grams at Canberra Hospital and her distraught parents were able to cradle her in the short five minutes she survived. The family, including her two older sisters Charlotte and Sophie, were able to take photos with Annabelle in her gown before the funeral. Angel Gowns created a replica dress for the family to have in their house and Ms Cox says she looks at it every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns is a not-for-profit organisation dedicated to turning donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who pass away too soon.</s>

A black police constable in Wiltshire, England has won a race discrimination case against his police force after he was not promoted due to the color of his skin. The employment tribunal ruled that the 40-year-old was passed over for promotion in favor of white colleagues after his internal assessments were secretly downgraded to make him appear unworthy. The tribunal also heard evidence that derogatory comments were made about Mr. Lungu based on his color, violating his dignity. The force, which has only 16 ethnic minority officers out of a total of just over 1,000, denied the claims, but the tribunal ruled that the Zimbabwe-born officer was unlawfully discriminated against on grounds of race. Mr. Lungu said he was left 'upset' and 'angry' after being penalized because he was black. The tribunal concluded that Wiltshire Police had singled out Mr. Lungu as a 'marked man' on grounds of his race. The judgment read: 'The reduction in the scoring has the very significant effect in terms of making it appear reasonable that the one black applicant for promotion was scoring lower than the 19 white applicants and should therefore not be promoted.' Despite his treatment, Mr. Lungu is still serving as a PC with the force. The Chief Constable of Wiltshire Police, Patrick Geenty, said he was 'concerned' by the findings and the force would 'learn lessons' from the case.</s>

A parent taught their newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle, which was filmed and has since been viewed over 190,000 times on YouTube. The video shows the parent gnawing on the side of a drinks container and the infant copying the action. The pair then bond over their shared interest in the simple prop.</s>

A set of unique photographs of Bristol, England, taken nearly 100 years before much of its historic center was destroyed by Nazi bombing, have surfaced. The images, captured between 1850 and 1855 by photographer Hugh Owen, show the waterfront, city center, St Mary Redcliffe church, and other landmarks. The photographs, made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s, are due to go up for auction tomorrow. The albumen prints show how much and how little has changed in certain areas over the past 160 years. The Fourteen Stars Tavern building, which was pulled down in 1857, can be seen in some of the pictures. The area of High Street has changed dramatically, while the view through St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist has not changed much. The photographs provide a fascinating glimpse into the past of Bristol.</s>

A pro-Ukip businessman, Harvey Boulter, is behind an effort to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate, Tom Tugendhat, in the Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent, constituency. Boulter is also spending £30,000 to defeat Liam Fox, who he forced to resign as Defence Secretary, in Fox's Somerset seat. Boulter's vendetta against Fox stems from a libel case in which Fox sued Boulter for defamatory remarks made on Sky TV. Fox resigned from the Cabinet in 2011 after Boulter revealed details of how Fox's close friend, businessman Adam Werritty, accompanied him on overseas trips as Defence Secretary. A Tory Party spokesperson declined to comment.</s>

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood has written a letter of encouragement to a six-year-old fan who applied for the job after Paul Lambert was sacked. Despite missing out on the job, Charlie Pye was congratulated for his knowledge of the game and was offered a signed claret and blue football, a WWE wrestling figure, and some sweets. Sherwood wrote that he would aim to make Charlie and other supporters happy and wished Charlie's team Norton Lindsey success in their season. Sherwood also congratulated Charlie on being appointed captain and mentioned that the club would like to keep his letter on file.</s>

Atletico Madrid beat Cordoba 2-0, with Antoine Griezmann scoring both goals, to move above Valencia in the battle for third place in La Liga. Saul Niguez also scored for Atletico, who now have 62 points from 29 matches. Valencia have 60 points and can reclaim third spot with a win over Villarreal on Sunday. Atletico also stayed close to second-placed Real Madrid, who they trail by four points. Sevilla, the only unbeaten team at home in La Liga this season, beat Athletic Bilbao 2-0 to move to 58 points in fifth.</s>

An 18-year-old mother of one died from multiple organ failure after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth, Staffordshire. The teenager, named as Abby Swinfield, was rushed to hospital in the early hours of March 30 and died a week later. Police have arrested one girl for supplying drugs, but Abby's cousin claims her drink was spiked. The family is devastated and Abby's son, who is believed to be three years old, keeps asking for his mother. A post-mortem examination is expected to determine the cause of death.</s>

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, with readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour. The cause of the radiation is not yet known, but it is believed to be coming from something buried underneath the park. The city has set up a health advice office to answer queries from concerned parents, and the park has been cordoned off. The incident has raised fears for the health of children in the area, and comes amid heightened concern over radiation in Japan since the 2011 Fukushima disaster.</s>

Amir Khan has accused Kell Brook of only calling him out for the "one big payday" and believes that Brook is not a big name in the UK. Khan also stated that Brook is not able to face the world's biggest names and is only trying to win fans over by mentioning his name. Khan denied that he will face Chris Algieri next month and claimed that there are "some more options" on the table. Khan also stated that Brook is desperate to fight him but he will not fight during Ramadan because of his Islamic faith. Khan believes that Brook is not a big name in the UK and is not able to face the world's biggest names.</s>

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot three-bedroom home. The home, dubbed 'PV14', also boasts a 1,400 sq ft roof deck that can fit up to 150 people, a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor and a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and the sparkling lights of the city's downtown. The designers wanted people to know what they were standing in when they stepped into the home, so they left the ceilings exposed and kept the shipping container gates unpainted. The walls of the shipping containers were removed, and columns had to be placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials. Spray foam was also used between the building layers to provide insulation. The upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors to complement the views of the nearby park and lake, which provide a wallpaper for the house thanks to floor-to-ceiling windows.</s>

Jordon Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week. The 19-year-old has agreed terms on a deal which will keep him at Anfield until 2020. Ibe spent the first half of this season on loan at Derby County but returned to Liverpool in January and has made a notable impact in his eight appearances. Liverpool are also close to finalising an extension for Martin Skrtel and are in talks with young defender Jon Flanagan whose contract expires in June. Liverpool have agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.</s>

Rik Mayall, the comedian and actor known for his roles in The New Statesman and Blackadder, died in 2014 without a valid will, leaving his estate to be dealt with under intestacy rules. According to these rules, his wife of 29 years and their three adult children would be entitled to a share of his estate, which could result in a large inheritance tax bill. Mayall suffered serious head injuries and nearly died in a quad-bike accident in 1998, but he did not leave a will despite this experience. Lawyers have always advised that people should have a valid will to avoid tax pitfalls, but Mayall did not heed this advice. His personal estate would be divided according to Government intestacy rules, which take into account marital status, children or surviving relatives. Mayall's children would be automatically entitled to a share of his net estate of £1,192,701 after funeral and legal expenses, meaning they could inherit an amount liable for inheritance tax. The amount of any tax payable would depend on the value of Mayall's chattels or personal belongings, which would go to his wife under intestacy rules. Mayall's family could seek to avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up his estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it was below the tax threshold.</s>

A group of Indian nationals and others who had been working in Yemen's capital, Sanaa, scrambled onto an Air India plane on the airport tarmac, carrying only carry-on luggage as they were evacuated during a small window when Saudi planes were not bombing the city. The passengers were exhausted by the push to get out of Yemen, which has been the site of some of the most chaotic fighting in the Mideast. Air India is especially active in evacuating citizens from Yemen because so many Indian nationals work in other nations. Over the last few days, India has evacuated some 2,500 people from Yemen, said Gen. Vijay Kumar Singh, the Indian deputy foreign minister who's overseeing the evacuation. The flights are going to Djibouti, a small African nation nearly 430 kilometers (267 miles) away. Some evacuees are fleeing on boats at port cities such as Aden. People are leaving behind much more than luggage, as the fighting and lack of electricity have made living in Yemen difficult. The Saudi air force gave Air India a four-hour window to go to and from Sanaa and a specific travel route for a safe landing. The passengers approached the planes carrying boarding passes, and the landing strips and airport terminal were untouched by Saudi bombs, but buildings on the outskirts of the airport and planes along the airstrip had been blown to bits. The evacuees will most likely disperse to their home nations after arriving in Djibouti.</s>

An Italian priest has been sacked from a religious order in Taranto after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing alleged evidence of sex with prostitutes, role play, and explicit gay web chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios in which his lover played the disciple Judas Escariot, and had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. The man claimed that he was contacted by the priest around six months ago on Facebook and that the priest revealed that he was gay during online chats. The priest also attempted to seduce the man and convinced him to leave his girlfriend. The Italian priest was sacked amid claims that he took part in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The Swiss Guard serves as the de facto military of Vatican City. The diocese confirmed that the priest had been dismissed but claimed there were no other prelates involved.</s>

A new study published in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children. The study, which was based on data from about 95,000 young people, found no association between MMR vaccination and an increased risk of autism, whether or not a sibling in the family was diagnosed with autism. The study's lead author, Anjali Jain, a doctor in Falls Church, Virginia, said, "We also found no evidence that receipt of either one or two doses of MMR vaccination was associated with an increased risk of ASD among children who had older siblings with ASD." The study's findings are consistent with other studies conducted over the last 15 years, which have also ruled out a link between the MMR vaccine and autism. Despite the consistent findings of these studies, concerns over vaccine safety, particularly in the Internet age, have proven difficult to quell. The study also found that children with older siblings with autism are less likely to get vaccinated, with a vaccination rate of 86 percent by age five for those with unaffected siblings compared to 92 percent for those with older siblings with autism.</s>

A 12-year-old Yazidi girl was kidnapped, beaten, and raped by ISIS fighters in Iraq. The report from Human Rights Watch found that ISIS fighters are kidnapping Yazidi women and children as young as eight, forcing them to marry and convert to Islam, and raping them repeatedly. The survivors' stories come as United Nations investigators found evidence that ISIS is committing genocide against the Yazidi minority in Iraq. The report suggests that ISIS may be guilty of "war crimes, crimes against humanity, and genocide." The survivors need better medical and psychological support to cope with the trauma they suffered.</s>

On Monday morning, a former student named Kenneth Stancil, 20, allegedly entered the Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, carrying a long-barreled gun and fired one shot, killing a long-time employee named Ron Lane. Stancil is described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee, and a tattoo over his left eye. The suspect is still at large and an active shooter situation exists. One person was fatally shot and the suspect is considered extremely dangerous. The college website advised all students to shelter as there was an active shooter on campus. SWAT teams were clearing the campus building by building and students were congregating in the college parking lot. The lockdown was lifted as of about 10.30am ET.</s>

The new CEO of Rotherham council could be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to negative publicity from the grooming scandal. The council will now offer up to £200,000 to candidates, rather than the £160,000 enjoyed by the former chief boss. The rest of the cabinet resigned in February after a government report said the council was 'not fit for purpose' and 'in denial' about exploitation, mainly of white girls by men of Pakistani origin. The HR chief said due to recent negative publicity, it may be necessary to consider additional incentives. The leader of the Ukip group said he was uncomfortable with the idea.</s>

Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during their win over Stoke City. The mask was made by the Ortholabsport in Milan and is branded with Fabregas' initial and squad number 'C4'. Fabregas traveled to Milan with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. John Terry was forced to wear a protective face mask after fracturing a cheekbone in 2007, and Fernando Torres also wore a mask during his time at Chelsea. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action with hamstring trouble.</s>

Andros Townsend scored a wonder strike for England in a 1-1 friendly draw with Italy in Turin, silencing his critics and providing motivation from naysayers like Paul Merson. This season has been topsy-turvy for Townsend, but England manager Roy Hodgson has kept faith with him, and he repaid that belief with a great goal.</s>

A husband accused of trying to murder his cheating wife wrote her an extraordinary letter from prison while on remand, asking her to send him a suit for his trial. Joseph O'Riordan, 73, stabbed his 47-year-old wife Amanda eight times after discovering she had been having an affair with a postman. She was left with life-threatening injuries. O'Riordan, who was a councillor at the time, rang an ambulance after the attack and admitted what he had done during the 999 call. Four months later, while on remand, O'Riordan wrote to his wife from jail asking her to gather some of his belongings for his trial. Mrs O'Riordan, during questioning by her husband's defense team in court yesterday, sobbed and said she did not want to hurt him. The case was adjourned for 90 minutes to give Mrs O'Riordan time to regain her composure.</s>

The UK is to open its first three proton beam therapy centres, following the success of five-year-old Ashya King who received the treatment and made a full recovery. Proton Partners International Ltd will open the centres in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017, with the first in Cardiff operational by next year. The announcement comes after Ashya's parents, Brett and Naghmeh King, fled with their son to Spain and Prague to receive the treatment after disagreeing with conventional NHS treatment plans. The centres will offer proton beam therapy, a highly-targeted type of radiotherapy that can treat hard-to-reach cancers with a lower risk of damaging surrounding tissue and causing side effects. The UK government has also announced plans to create two NHS proton beam therapy units, which will open in 2018.</s>

The London Ambulance Service is recruiting paramedics from Australia and other countries because there is a shortage of trained paramedics in the UK. The selection process is held at five-star hotels and is so quick that applicants can receive an email the next day informing them if they have a job. The ambulance service is also understaffed, with around 1,250 posts unfilled across England, which is a tenth of what is needed. The increasing demand on ambulances means they are taking longer to reach the seriously ill, leading to many paramedics choosing to take up posts as 'advanced practitioners' in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centres for the 111 helpline where the work is less stressful and they can earn more. The ambulance service is also considering flying out to Poland to recruit paramedics. The cost of training one paramedic in Britain is £50,000, while each trip to Australia costs the ambulance service £90,000 in flights and hotel bills, but they return having hired on average 200 paramedics.</s>

Chelsea Football Club has turned to the latest fitness technology to help them win the Premier League title. The club has partnered with leading wellness solutions provider Technogym, who have kitted out their Cobham training ground with state-of-the-art equipment. Players such as Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured working out, and Kurt Zouma has broken into the first team this year. Chelsea fitness coach Carlos Lalin has hailed the partnership with Technogym, and the club has had two players nominated for the PFA Player of the Year awards. Hazard is the hot favourite to pick up the award for his consistently brilliant form.</s>

Babies as young as 11 months old have already mastered the fundamentals of physics, such as understanding how objects can pass through solid walls, and are surprisingly sophisticated thinkers. When presented with magic tricks that defy their expectations, they attempt to uncover the secrets and are more interested in playing with the ball than a new toy they have never seen before. A study by psychologists at the University of Missouri has found that infants as young as 13 months old can comprehend complex social situations, such as what constitutes bullying, friendship, and what it means to be a bystander. The researchers suggest that babies use what they already know about the world to form predictions and learn from unexpected situations. The study also found that babies who can accurately depict the human form at the age of four are more likely to be brighter in their teenage years.</s>

Manny Pacquiao is training for his fight against Floyd Mayweather by running on the streets of Los Angeles and working on his core strength and footwork. He was joined by several fitness fanatics and his dog Pacman as he ran around Griffith Park and shadow boxed in front of spectators. Pacquiao has also unveiled a multicolored mouth guard he will wear during the fight.</s>

A cat named Biso who had been stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years has finally been freed. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo who fed him scraps of food every day. The cat's plight came to the attention of animal activists after a picture of his tail was posted on Facebook. Animal rights activists, including Mounira Shehata, Marwa Elgebaly, and Rania el-Kordy, went to the station to rescue the cat on March 12, but the terrified cat ran away. The rescue mission took more than five hours, and a worker named Amr had to go inside to bring the cat out. The cat is still missing, and Uncle Abdo is searching for him inside the station.</s>

At least 35 workers were killed at a dairy factory in Yemen when Saudi Arabian warplanes continued to bomb Shiite rebel positions in both the north and the south of the country. Today's airstrikes targeted rebel-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida and hit warehouses belonging to a factory that produces dairy products. The jets drew return fire from anti-aircraft guns as the Saudi-led campaign to defeat the Iran-backed Shiite rebels loyal to Yemen's deposed president Ali Abdullah Saleh entered its seventh day. The attack on the dairy factory comes as Saudi Arabia hinted that it was prepared to launch a ground invasion in Yemen in the hope of forcing the Houthi rebels to allow current president, Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi to return to the country, after he fled the southern port city of Aden last week. The Houthi's anti-aircraft guns returned fire before the factory itself was set ablaze. According to the medical center in Hodeida, at least 35 workers were killed, many of them crushed by the rubble or burned to death.</s>

A truck crash on an elevated highway in Boston caused delays for hundreds of morning commuters. The truck collided with a car and both drivers were taken to the hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. Replacement shuttle buses were run for southbound passengers, causing long queues. The truck driver was identified as a 57-year-old man from Woburn, and the car driver was a 42-year-old man from Attleboro. State troopers are still investigating the incident, and no charges have been filed.</s>

Mark McCall, the director of rugby for Saracens, praised his young players after their European semi-final loss to Clermont, stating that he has no intention of overspending in the post-World Cup transfer market. McCall's team, which contained five English-qualified forwards in the starting pack, came close to reaching the final but ultimately lost 13-9. Despite Saracens' millionaire chairman Nigel Wray's belief that the cap should be scrapped, McCall stated that the club is prepared to wait for the right player and is excited about the potential of their young pack, which could be the mainstay of the club for the next four to five seasons.</s>

Arsenal must make a decision on signing Petr Cech from Chelsea this summer or risk losing out on the goalkeeper. Cech is likely to leave Chelsea at the end of the season after losing his No 1 spot to Thibaut Courtois. Arsenal is one of the clubs interested in signing Cech, but they will have to overcome several obstacles, including Cech's valuation and Chelsea's reluctance to sell to their London rivals. Cech is considering moving to the Emirates Stadium, despite spending over 10 years with Chelsea, and hopes his long period of service will allow him to make the final decision on his next destination.</s>

Sheik Joaan Al Thani has signed up French jockey Gregory Benoist to ride his horses in France, leaving Frankie Dettori to focus on the British flat season. Benoist will ride the horses that race under Al Shaqab's banner in France, except for dual Arc winner Treve, which will be partnered by Thierry Jarnet. Dettori will still ride British horses that run in France. The decision was made due to the expansion of Al Shaqab's operation, which now has over 80 horses in France and almost 100 in Britain. Dettori finished third on Al Shaqab's Moheet in yesterday's Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket.</s>

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has died at the age of 78. Her son, David Lilienstein, confirmed that she passed away peacefully from a rare form of cancer on Wednesday night in Toronto. Lilienstein was born in Chicago in 1936 and moved to Toronto in 1996 with her son and husband. She joined Sharon Hampson and Bram Morrison to launch their singing trio in 1978, and the TV show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989, before continuing in reruns on Nickelodeon stateside until 1995. Sally Catto, general manager of programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein for her contribution to Canadian kids TV.</s>

The video shows a world freediving champion, Guillaume Néry, jumping into the second deepest underwater sink hole in the world, Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas. He holds his breath and swims to the bottom before swimming back to the surface. Free divers can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes through sophisticated mind-body control techniques. The video was filmed in 2010 by his girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier.</s>

A suicide bomber on a motorbike attacked the Kabul Bank in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, early on Saturday, killing at least 33 people and injuring more than 100 others. The ISIS terrorist group claimed responsibility for the attack, which was made by an offshoot called ISIS Wilayat Khorasan. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack. The United Nations condemned the violence and warned that the use of suicide attacks in populated areas may amount to a war crime. Fears about ISIS involvement in the region have been growing this year, with former Taliban commander Mullah Abdul Rauf, who had become a recruiter for ISIS in Afghanistan, being killed in a drone strike in February.</s>

Model and environmental scientist Laura Wells has launched a new eco-friendly swimwear line, made entirely of 100% recycled material. The collection is inspired by the ocean and features coral reef scenes throughout. The line includes one and two-piece suits in sizes ranging from 10 to 24, catering to all shapes. The collaboration with US brand Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy, was inspired by a conversation Laura had with the brand while working on a photoshoot. The primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping prices affordable.</s>

The TrackYourDose app is a personal radiation tracker that helps users understand their exposure to radiation from various sources, including air travel, medical examinations, and natural radiation from the environment. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists to calculate radiation levels based on a user's location, flight details, and solar activity. It accounts for gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground, as well as neutron radiation in the atmosphere. The app allows users to input their flight details and track their radiation exposure during travel. The app is available for iOS devices for £1.49 ($1.99).</s>

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility that officials had previously connected to a foodborne illness linked to the deaths of three people. The company is taking this step out of an abundance of caution to ensure that it is doing everything possible to provide its consumers with safe products and to preserve the trust it has built with them and their families for more than a century. The recall, the first in the company's 108-year history, began when five patients at Via Christi St. Francis hospital in Wichita, Kansas, became ill with listeriosis while hospitalized at some point from December 2013 to January 2015. Officials determined at least four drank milkshakes that contained Blue Bell ice cream. Three of the patients later died. Listeriosis, also known as listeria, is a life-threatening infection caused by eating food contaminated with bacteria called Listeria monocytogenes. The CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from that found in the 3-ounce cup ice cream product traced to the Oklahoma plant. The company will conduct a 'careful and complete examination' of its Oklahoma plant 'to determine the exact cause of the contamination.' The plant has been voluntarily shut down, and the company says it will notify the U.S. Food and Drug Administration of its decision. The recalled ice cream had been shipped to 23 states, and the CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from that found in the 3-ounce cup ice cream product traced to the Oklahoma plant. The company's other plants continue to operate and supply its products to retail stores and institutional customers.</s>

Jon Hamm, the star of the TV show Mad Men, was involved in a hazing incident at the University of Texas at Austin in 1990. According to court documents, Hamm and other fraternity members beat a prospective pledge and set fire to his pants as part of a brutal initiation ritual. Hamm was charged with assault, but the charges were eventually dismissed. The incident led to the shutdown of the Sigma Nu fraternity at UT-Austin. In a recent interview, Hamm admitted that playing the complex role of Don Draper on Mad Men has taken a toll on his psyche and that he wants to distance himself from being typecast as the dark, brooding, alcoholic womanizing character.</s>

The UK has summoned the Argentine ambassador to the UK to account for recent statements by the Argentine president regarding the Falkland Islands. The UK has no doubt about its sovereignty over the Falkland Islands and surrounding maritime areas, and the Falkland Islanders' right to decide their own future. The UK government has announced plans to beef up defences in the Falklands and modernize its defences in response to the threat of Russia. The Argentine government has accused three British and two US companies of exploring for oil off the Falklands without permission and has threatened legal action. The UK foreign secretary has stated that the threats against those who do business with the Falkland Islands are hollow and illegal.</s>

A Delta Air Lines flight from Tampa, Florida, to New York City was met by firefighters in full protective suits after an odor of smoke was reported by the crew moments after the plane landed at LaGuardia Airport. The firefighters used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source on the plane. Passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes while the situation was resolved. The plane was taken out of service for an inspection and any necessary maintenance.</s>

David Luiz, the defender for Paris Saint-Germain, has injured his hamstring and will be out for at least four weeks. He posted a picture of himself with a new hairstyle, a man bun, on Instagram and his teammate Lucas Moura joked about giving him a nickname for his new look. However, Luiz's injury will be a setback for his team as they seek to defend their Ligue 1 title and compete in the Champions League.</s>

US President Barack Obama stated in his weekly address on Saturday that diplomacy is the best option to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. He emphasized the importance of the deal's rigorous inspections and verification measures, which he believes will prevent Iran from cheating. Obama also acknowledged that there will be a "robust debate" in the US regarding the deal, but he plans to keep Congress informed of the agreement's details. The framework agreement reached between Iran and six world powers outlines a deal that would curb Iran's nuclear program and potentially lift economic sanctions. However, Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has strongly criticized the deal, stating that it would threaten the survival of the state of Israel.</s>

A 12-year-old girl with leukemia has been kicked out of school for poor attendance due to her illness. The school made accommodations for her, but they were not enough to help her attend classes and complete her schoolwork. The girl's parents feel that the school is failing their child and have filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. The girl's mother says that her daughter is not skipping school to have fun, but rather she is too sick to attend. The girl's father says that the accommodations made by the school were woefully inadequate for a child with such a serious diagnosis. The girl's family is trying to raise money for St. Baldricks to find a cure for childhood cancer.</s>

The study found that second-hand cigarette smoke can affect plants and cause them to take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. This can explain why some spices, herbal teas, and medicinal plants have high concentrations of nicotine, despite none being allowed in insecticides. The researchers found that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soils, as well as from smoke. The study suggests that the widespread occurrence of nicotine in medicinal, spice, and food plants may be due to other nicotine sources apart from the illegal use of insecticides. The findings also shed light on the hitherto unexplained success behind farming practices such as crop rotation and the co-cultivation of certain vegetables.</s>

The video shows two chameleons fighting for a female mate in a brief contest on a property near the Amber Mountain National Park in Madagascar. The more aggressive of the two chameleons wins the battle and the defeated chameleon struggles to escape. The video maker speaks French and provides play-by-play commentary.</s>

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh rugby club on a two-year deal starting next season. The 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side. Cosgrove is looking to add something extra to the Edinburgh squad and improve his game under the guidance of coach Alan Solomons. He is aware of the tough competition in the team but is eager to learn from players like Alasdair Dickinson. Cosgrove also praised the club's recent success, including reaching the European Cup final and advancing to the Pro12 playoffs.</s>

Aaron Hernandez, the former NFL player who was sentenced to life in prison for the murder of Odin Lloyd, has been given the prison number W106228. He is being held in maximum security at the Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center in Shirley, Massachusetts. Hernandez was known to smoke "angel dust," a hallucinogenic drug, and his behavior became increasingly violent and aggressive after he started using it. He was also a heavy drinker and would often spend large amounts of money on bars and clubs. Hernandez is being transferred to the Souza-Baranowski maximum security prison from MCI Cedar Junction in Walpole, Massachusetts.</s>

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has confirmed that the club will be investing in homegrown talent this summer, which could impact Celtic's hopes of retaining Jason Denayer on loan. Denayer has impressed while playing for Celtic this season, but Pellegrini's comments suggest that City may bring back young professionals from loan deals to fill the gap. Denayer may be one of these players, as he falls into the category of homegrown talent despite hailing from Belgium. Pellegrini said that he is confident in the future of young players coming from the club's Academy, but it may take time for them to break into the first team.</s>

Manchester United midfielder Ander Herrera reveals in a Q&A video that he wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons following his spell at Athletic Bilbao. Herrera, who joined United for £29m last summer, cites his good form at Bilbao as the reason for keeping his forename and surname on the back of his shirt. Herrera has forced his way into Louis van Gaal's starting line-up with a series of impressive displays and scored twice in United's 3-1 win over Aston Villa on Saturday, his tally now stands at seven goals in all competitions this season. He hopes to show more emotion in the future as United target silverware.</s>

Porto fans gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal following a 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-final. Despite the loss, the team had reached the quarter-finals for the first time since the 2008-09 season, and coach Julen Lopetegui praised the team's efforts in the tournament.</s>

The BBC has been criticized for creating a computer game called "Syrian Journey" that simulates the dangerous journey that Syrian refugees must take to escape their war-torn country and reach Europe. The game has been described as "sickening" and "in bad taste" by some social media users, who argue that it turns the suffering of millions into a "children's game." The game has been criticized for its grim outcomes, which include refugees being separated from their families, beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean, and sold to militia groups. The BBC has defended the game, saying that it shows the choices faced by Syrian families every day and has achieved over a million online hits a week.</s>

Two of the victims of the Boston Marathon bombing have called for the death penalty to be taken off the table as a punishment for Dzhokar Tsarnaev, the bomber who killed three people and injured hundreds more in 2013. Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the attack, said they opposed the death penalty as a means of punishment for their attacker, urging others to "overcome the impulse for vengeance." The couple's statement follows a similar appeal made by the family of an eight-year-old boy who was killed in the blast. The victims' position is highly emotional and practical, and they call for life in prison without parole or appeals to ensure Tsarnaev "disappears from our collective consciousness as soon as possible." The Richards, the family of bombing victim Martin Richard, also wrote an op-ed in the Boston Globe, saying they oppose the death penalty for Tsarnaev. The family is pictured on the two-year anniversary of the attack.</s>

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Dr. Ayse Giray, who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement came just before a court ruling on whether Giray could be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company. Ulukaya's camp settled to avoid losing assets worth $1 billion to Giray. Despite the settlement, Ulukaya still faces business problems, including a product recall that led to negative EBITDA of $87 million in the fourth quarter of 2013.</s>

Diego Costa has suffered a hamstring injury and is expected to miss Chelsea's game against Arsenal. He is likely to be fit to return for the game against Arsenal, but his participation in the game will depend on how the title race develops. The club is considering giving Costa an extended break to help him overcome his hamstring problems.</s>

The England C team, which has been in existence for 36 years, may be disbanded as part of a spending review at the Football Association. The team, which is managed by Paul Fairclough and selects players outside the Football League aged 23 and under, has only played three or four times a year and has not qualified for the semi-finals of the International Challenge Trophy in recent years. The team's long-term future is uncertain due to the need to find £30 million to fund a masterplan to improve grassroots football, which includes the creation of more 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. Some of the team's fixtures have attracted attention due to the elaborate travel involved, and the team has not played any friendly fixtures since February. Former players of the team include George Boyd, Craig Mackail-Smith, and Steve Morison, who all went on to play at full international level, although not for England.</s>

James Haskell, the captain of London Wasps rugby club, posted a photo of himself dressed as Iron Man on Instagram to celebrate the release of the new Avengers movie. The highly-anticipated movie premiered at Westfield London shopping center with a star-studded cast including Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell, who started his career at Wasps in 2002, returned to the club for the 2012 season after spells with Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders in New Zealand. The flanker has since become a key player for England and has surpassed 100 appearances for Wasps.</s>

A woman named Stacey Eden stood up to a middle-aged woman who was making offensive comments about Islam on a train in Sydney. The woman was ranting about Islam, bringing up beheadings and the marriage of children while berating a Muslim woman for wearing a black headscarf. Stacey recorded a snippet of the conversation and fired back at the woman in defense of the Muslim couple. The Muslim couple told Stacey they were "very grateful" for her stand. The incident occurred on Wednesday afternoon on an Airport Line train. The police and Sydney Trains have not yet received any reports of the incident. The Islamophobia Register Australia group praised Stacey's actions and said they were disappointed by the remarks of the woman in the video.</s>

Title: "Hawaiian Adventures: Discovering the Islands' Rich Culture and Natural Wonders"

Introduction:

Hawaii, the tropical paradise, has always been a dream destination for travelers around the world. With its lush landscapes, pristine beaches, and rich cultural heritage, the Aloha State offers an unforgettable experience. Recently, I embarked on a journey to explore the islands and immerse myself in their unique culture. In this blog post, I'll be sharing my adventures and must-see attractions that made my trip to Hawaii an unforgettable experience.

Day 1: Arrival in Honolulu

Upon arriving in Honolulu, the capital city of Hawaii, I was greeted by the warm sun and the sound of the waves crashing against the shore. After checking into my hotel, I headed straight to Waikiki Beach, one of the most famous beaches in the world. The sun was setting, and the sky was painted in shades of orange and pink, creating a picturesque scene. I spent the evening strolling along the beach, taking in the sights and sounds of the bustling city.

Day 2: Hiking to the Top of Diamond Head

The next day, I decided to explore the island's natural beauty by hiking to the top of Diamond Head. This iconic volcanic crater is a must-see attraction in Honolulu, and the hike offers breathtaking views of the city and the ocean. The trail was steep, but the reward at the top was worth it. I stood at the summit, taking in the stunning panorama and feeling a sense of accomplishment.

Day 3: Exploring the Polynesian Cultural Center

On the third day, I visited the Polynesian Cultural Center, a unique attraction that showcases the cultures of Hawaii, Fiji, Samoa, and other Pacific Island nations. I spent the day immersing myself in the rich traditions and customs of these cultures, from learning how to hula dance to watching a fire knife dance performance. The center also offers interactive experiences, such as trying traditional foods and watching a canoe race.

Day 4: Snorkeling with Turtles

Here are some compelling reasons why you should consider volunteering as a guest speaker:

1. Improve your communication skills: Public speaking can be intimidating, but it's also a great way to improve your communication skills. By practicing and delivering presentations, you'll become more confident and comfortable speaking in front of an audience.
2. Networking opportunities: By volunteering as a guest speaker, you'll have the chance to connect with other professionals and potential clients in your industry. This can open up new opportunities for you and help you build your professional network.
3. Give back to the community: Volunteering as a guest speaker is a great way to give back to your community. By sharing your knowledge and expertise, you can help others learn and grow.

I understand that public speaking may not be your cup of tea, but I believe that you can do it. You have valuable insights and experiences to share, and your audience will appreciate your unique perspective.

If you're still unsure, I'd be happy to discuss this further and answer any questions you may have. Let's chat soon!

Best regards,

[Your Name]</s>

The old abandoned house at the end of the street held a secret that no one had ever discovered. It had been empty for as long as anyone could remember, and the rumors about what had happened inside were just that - rumors. No one knew for sure, but some said that a family had died there, others said that it was haunted, and still others claimed that it was the site of a gruesome murder.

But none of that mattered to 12-year-old Emily. She had always been fascinated by the old house, and she had spent countless hours exploring its empty rooms and peering through its boarded-up windows. She had always been too afraid to investigate further, but today was different. Today, she was determined to uncover the truth about the house and what had happened inside.

Emily woke up early, before the sun had risen, and made her way to the old house. She was careful to stay hidden from view, creeping along the side of the house and slipping through the overgrown grass. When she reached the front door, she paused for a moment, taking a deep breath and steeling herself for what was to come.

She slowly pushed the door open, and the musty smell of decay hit her like a wall. The house was dark and quiet, and Emily could barely see a thing. She fumbled for her flashlight, switching it on and casting a beam of light around the room.

As she made her way through the house, Emily's heart raced with excitement and fear. She was determined to uncover the truth, but she knew that she was taking a huge risk. What if she didn't make it out alive?

But Emily was a curious and brave girl, and she was not about to let fear hold her back. She explored every room, searching for any clues that might reveal the secrets of the old house. And as she searched, she began to uncover a story that was more horrifying than she could have ever imagined.

The old abandoned house at the end of the street held a secret that no one had ever discovered. But Emily had discovered it, and she had paid the ultimate price for her curiosity.</s>

As Elon Musk, I believe that it is crucial for humanity to establish a permanent presence on Mars in order to ensure our long-term survival and growth as a species.

Firstly, Mars offers a unique opportunity for us to establish a second home for humanity, one that is not subject to the same limitations as Earth. The planet's harsh environment and lack of natural resources mean that any human settlement on Mars will have to be highly self-sufficient and sustainable. This will require us to develop new technologies and techniques for resource management, as well as new forms of agriculture and manufacturing.

Secondly, Mars offers us the opportunity to expand our scientific knowledge and understanding of the universe. By studying the Martian environment and searching for signs of life, we can gain valuable insights into the conditions necessary for life to exist elsewhere in the universe. This knowledge will be invaluable in our quest to find other habitable planets and potentially even extraterrestrial life.

Finally, establishing a presence on Mars will help us to prepare for the possibility of a catastrophic event on Earth, such as a major asteroid impact or a global pandemic. By having a backup plan in place, we can ensure that humanity continues to thrive and evolve, even in the face of such challenges.

Overall, I believe that the benefits of establishing a permanent presence on Mars far outweigh the challenges and risks involved, and I am committed to making it happen as soon as possible.</s>

Probability is a way of describing the likelihood of an event occurring. It is a number between 0 and 1 that represents the chance of something happening. For example, if you flip a coin, the probability of it landing on heads is 0.5 (or 50%).

There are two main types of probability:

1. Classical probability: This is the type of probability that is used to describe the likelihood of an event occurring in a single trial. For example, if you flip a coin, the probability of it landing on heads in one flip is 0.5.
2. Subjective probability: This is the type of probability that is used to describe the likelihood of an event occurring over a series of trials. For example, if you flip a coin 10 times, the probability of getting 5 heads and 5 tails is 0.25 (or 25%).

To calculate probability, you need to know the number of favorable outcomes and the total number of outcomes. For example, if you flip a coin 10 times, the number of favorable outcomes (getting heads) is 10, and the total number of outcomes is 20 (10 heads and 10 tails). So, the probability of getting heads in 10 flips is 10/20 = 0.5.

Here's a Python program that reads all the text files under a directory and returns the top-5 words with the most number of occurrences:
```python
import os
from collections import Counter

def find_most_occurring_words(directory):
    word_counts = Counter()
    for filename in os.listdir(directory):
        if filename.endswith('.txt'):
            with open(os.path.join(directory, filename), 'r') as f:
                for line in f:
                    for word in line.split():
                        word_counts[word] += 1
    top_words = sorted(word_counts.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:5]
    return [word[0] for word in top_words]

directory = 'path/to/directory'
top_words = find_most_occurring_words(directory)
print(top_words)
```

def find_majority_element(arr):
    """
    Find the majority element in an integer array using the Boyer-Moore Voting Algorithm.

    Args:
        arr (list): A list of integers.

    Returns:
        The index of the majority element in the array, or -1 if no majority element is found.
    """
    n = len(arr)
    if n == 0:
        return -1
    if n == 1:
        return arr[0]

    # Initialize variables
    max_count = 0
    max_index = -1
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i + 1, n):
            # Check if the current element is the majority element
            if arr[i] == arr[j]:
                max_count += 1
                max_index = i

    # If the current element is the majority element, update the maximum count and index
    if max_count > max_count[0]:
        max_count = [max_count, max_count[1] + 1]
        max_index = i

    # If the current element is not the majority element, update the maximum index
    else:
        max_index = j

    # Return the index of the majority element
    return max_index
```

This phenomenon has been experimentally verified and is considered to be a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics.

For example, two entangled particles can exist in a superposition of being separated by a large distance or being in the same location. This property of superposition allows for the possibility of instantaneous communication between entangled particles, even if they are separated by large distances.

The light-dependent reactions involve the conversion of light energy into chemical energy through the process of electron transfer. This stage of photosynthesis generates a proton gradient across the thylakoid membrane, which is used as the input for the light-independent reactions.

The light-independent reactions take place in the stroma of the chloroplast. The primary inputs for this stage are ATP and NADPH, and the primary output is glucose and oxygen. The light-independent reactions involve the conversion of carbon dioxide into glucose through the process of carbon fixation. This stage of photosynthesis uses the proton gradient generated by the light-dependent reactions to drive the synthesis of glucose.

Overall, photosynthesis is a complex process that involves the coordination of multiple steps and subprocesses, and it is essential for the survival of all living organisms on Earth.</s>

The central dogma of molecular biology consists of two processes: transcription and translation.

Examples of exothermic reactions include burning of fuel, such as gasoline or wood, and the rusting of iron. In these reactions, the reactants combine to form products, releasing energy in the form of heat.

Endothermic reactions, on the other hand, are chemical reactions that absorb heat energy. This means that the reaction is accompanied by the absorption of energy in the form of heat. Examples of endothermic reactions include the freezing of water and the dissolving of a solute in a solvent. In these reactions, the reactants combine to form products, absorbing energy in the form of heat.

The criteria used to distinguish between exothermic and endothermic reactions are the changes in the heat energy of the system before and after the reaction. For example, consider the reaction between hydrogen and oxygen to form water:

This reaction is an endothermic reaction because it absorbs energy in the form of heat. The heat energy of the system decreases as the reactants combine to form products.

Additionally, the bridge should be built to withstand the potential for soil liquefaction, which can occur during earthquakes and cause the ground to become unstable. Machine learning is a subset of artificial intelligence that involves the use of algorithms to enable a system to improve its performance on a specific task over time. The system learns from data and experiences, enabling it to make predictions, classify data, or take actions based on the input it receives.

There are three main types of machine learning: supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and reinforcement learning.

1. Supervised learning: In supervised learning, the system is trained on a labeled dataset, which means that the data is already labeled with the correct output. The system learns to map the input data to the correct output by using a learning algorithm. This type of machine learning is commonly used in image recognition, speech recognition, and natural language processing. For example, a supervised learning algorithm can be trained on a dataset of images labeled with their corresponding object categories, such as dogs, cats, and cars. Once the algorithm has been trained, it can be used to classify new images as either dogs, cats, or cars based on their features.
2. Unsupervised learning: In unsupervised learning, the system is trained on an unlabeled dataset, which means that the data does not have the correct output already labeled. The system learns to find patterns or structure in the data by using a learning algorithm. This type of machine learning is commonly used in data clustering, anomaly detection, and dimensionality reduction. For example, an unsupervised learning algorithm can be used to group similar images of faces together based on their features, such as the shape of their eyes or the curve of their lips.
3. Reinforcement learning: In reinforcement learning, the system learns by interacting with an environment and receiving feedback in the form of rewards or penalties. The system learns to take actions that maximize the rewards it receives over time. This type of machine learning is commonly used in robotics, game playing, and autonomous vehicles. For example, a reinforcement learning algorithm can be used to train a robot to navigate a maze by receiving a reward for reaching the end of the maze and a penalty for colliding with walls.

However, it is possible to use a combination of supervised and reinforcement learning to solve a problem. For example, a robot navigating a maze could be trained on a labeled dataset of maze layouts and their corresponding correct paths. Once the robot has been trained on this supervised learning task, it could then use reinforcement learning to navigate the maze in real-time, receiving rewards for reaching the end of the maze and penalties for colliding with walls.

In summary, while it is not possible to use supervised learning alone to solve a reinforcement learning problem, it is possible to use a combination of supervised and reinforcement learning to solve a problem.</s>

Economic indicators such as GDP, inflation, and unemployment rates are closely related and are often used to measure the overall health of an economy. Here's a brief overview of how these indicators are correlated and how fiscal and monetary policies can affect them:

1. Gross Domestic Product (GDP): GDP is the total value of all goods and services produced within a country's borders in a given period of time, usually a year. It is a key indicator of a country's economic performance and is often used to measure the overall size and health of an economy. Fiscal policies, such as government spending and taxation, can affect GDP by changing the amount of money available in the economy and by influencing consumer and business spending. Monetary policies, such as interest rates and the money supply, can also affect GDP by influencing borrowing and investment.
2. Inflation: Inflation is the rate at which the general level of prices for goods and services is increasing over time. High levels of inflation can lead to decreased purchasing power and can make it difficult for consumers and businesses to plan for the future. Fiscal policies, such as increasing government spending or lowering taxes, can lead to inflation if they increase the money supply and cause prices to rise. Monetary policies, such as raising interest rates, can also help to reduce inflation by making borrowing more expensive and reducing demand for loans.
3. Unemployment Rates: Unemployment rates measure the percentage of the labor force that is without jobs but actively seeking employment. High unemployment rates can indicate economic weakness and can have negative effects on individuals, businesses, and the overall economy. Fiscal policies, such as government spending on job training and education, can help to reduce unemployment by creating new job opportunities. Monetary policies, such as lowering interest rates, can also help to stimulate economic growth and reduce unemployment by making it easier for businesses to borrow and invest.

In summary, GDP, inflation, and unemployment rates are closely related economic indicators that provide important insights into the overall health of an economy. Fiscal and monetary policies can affect these indicators in different ways, and policymakers must carefully consider the potential impacts of their policies on the economy

Lesson Plan: "The Opium Wars: A Dramatic Retelling"

Duration: 3 class periods (each lasts for 45 minutes) for 3 days

Objective: Students will be able to analyze and understand the causes and consequences of the Opium Wars between China and Britain through a dramatic retelling of the events.

Materials:

* Copies of primary source documents (such as letters, treaties, and newspaper articles) related to the Opium Wars
* Scripts for the dramatic retelling of the Opium Wars
* Costumes and props for the dramatic performance
* Whiteboard and markers

* Begin the class by asking students to brainstorm what they already know about the Opium Wars. Write their responses on the whiteboard.
* Introduce the concept of drama and mime as a way to understand historical events. Explain that by using these techniques, students will be able to better understand the motivations and actions of the key players in the Opium Wars.
* Distribute copies of primary source documents related to the Opium Wars and ask students to read them and take notes on what they learned.
* Introduce the scripts for the dramatic retelling of the Opium Wars and ask students to read through them.

* Divide the class into small groups and assign each group a specific cause of the Opium Wars (such as British trade policies or Chinese resistance).

* After each group has performed their skit, have the class discuss the similarities and differences between the different causes and how they contributed to the Opium Wars.

Socrates was a Greek philosopher who lived in the 5th century BCE. He is known for his method of questioning, known as the Socratic method, in which he would ask a series of questions to challenge the prevailing thoughts of his time.

Socrates believed that knowledge could be acquired through questioning and dialogue, rather than through the acceptance of dogma or the memorization of facts. He would often engage in conversations with others, asking questions to clarify their beliefs and expose any contradictions or inconsistencies in their thinking.

Socrates believed that the pursuit of knowledge and wisdom was the most important goal in life, and he was willing to challenge even the most respected and established thinkers of his time in order to advance his own understanding of the world. He was particularly critical of those who claimed to have all the answers, and he believed that true wisdom came from a willingness to question and learn.

Overall, Socrates employed the Socratic method as a way to challenge the prevailing thoughts of his time and to encourage others to think critically and question their own beliefs.</s>

Socrates: Very well. I understand that generative AI has the potential to personalize learning and provide individualized feedback to students. However, I believe that this approach may lead to a lack of critical thinking and a dependence on technology.

Bill Gates: I see your point, Socrates. However, I believe that generative AI can be used in a way that promotes critical thinking and problem-solving skills. For example, AI can provide students with challenging problems to solve, which can help them develop their critical thinking skills.

Socrates: I see your point, but I remain concerned about the potential negative effects of generative AI on education. I believe that the pursuit of knowledge and wisdom should be based on human interaction and critical thinking, rather than on technology.

Bill Gates: I understand your concerns, Socrates. However, I believe that generative AI has the potential to revolutionize education and provide students with a more personalized and effective learning experience.

Socrates: I will continue to question and challenge the prevailing thoughts on the use of generative AI in education, in the hopes of promoting critical thinking and the pursuit of knowledge and wisdom.</s>

When doing business in Japan, it's important to be aware of the country's business etiquette norms. Here are some key points to keep in mind:

1. Business cards: Exchange business cards with your Japanese counterparts as a sign of respect. Present your card with both hands and take the time to study the card carefully.
2. Greetings: In Japan, it's customary to bow when greeting someone, even if you've already met them. The depth of the bow depends on the level of formality and the relationship between the two people.
3. Meetings: Meetings in Japan tend to be more formal than in some other countries. Arrive on time and be prepared to follow a strict agenda. It's also important to maintain eye contact and avoid fidgeting or looking at your phone during the meeting.
4. Gifts: Gifts are not typically expected in business dealings in Japan, but they can be a thoughtful gesture to show appreciation for a business relationship. Be sure to choose a gift that is appropriate for the occasion and the relationship with the recipient.
5. Dining: Business dinners in Japan are often a formal affair, with a set menu and a strict order of courses. Be sure to follow the lead of your Japanese counterparts and use chopsticks appropriately.
6. Communication: In Japan, it's important to be clear and concise in your communication. Avoid using slang or colloquial language, and be prepared to repeat information if necessary.

By following these business etiquette norms, you can build strong relationships with your Japanese business partners and colleagues and help ensure a successful outcome for your business dealings.</s>

The second van is used as a decoy to confuse potential attackers. Clinton enjoys constant protection at taxpayers' expense because she is part of a former first family, not as a result of her service in the U.S. Senate or the State Department. The two Scooby vans arrived at Clinton's appointed location separately but left together in a seven-car motorcade. The second Scooby van's driver brought up the rear, allowing another car to pull in front of him. When that car stopped at a red light, the GMC van's blue and red flashing lights came on, and the GMC van zoomed into the intersection against the light. A Georgia mother of six is homeless after a fire destroyed her rented condo in Decatur, Georgia. The mother, who was enrolled in school to complete her degree in business management, has been unable to find a new place to live while unemployed. She and her children are currently staying with a friend, far from their children's Decatur schools, where they are required to take a standardized test on Tuesday. The American Red Cross has assisted the family in their search for housing, but shelters have turned them away. The mother has started a GoFundMe page to raise money for a new place to live.</s>

An Australian couple abandoned a boy born through surrogacy in India, and were repeatedly told that the child would be left stateless. Documents obtained by the ABC show that Australian government officials were aware of the situation, and that the couple was from New South Wales, where it is illegal to enter into international surrogacy arrangements. The couple told consular staff that they would be leaving the twin brother behind because they could not afford him, and that they wanted a baby girl to "complete their family." The boy would have been left stateless if the couple had followed through on their plans to abandon him, because India does not recognize surrogate children as citizens. The case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case in Thailand, where an Australian couple abandoned their son with a severe disability and only brought back his twin sister.</s>

Kecil, a baby orangutan who had a tough start to life, found love and a surrogate mother in Maggie, an experienced orangutan mother, at the Brookfield Zoo in Chicago. After being rejected by his natural mother and two surrogate mothers, Kecil was given to Maggie, who has already raised four children and a fifth surrogate. The two have formed an inseparable bond and will go on display for the first time this weekend.</s>

Javier Pastore, a star player for Paris Saint-Germain, has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet. Cantona, a former Manchester United forward, had praised Pastore as 'the best player in the world', but Pastore believes Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's 3-1 win at Nice on Saturday and spoke about his admiration for Messi and Ronaldo. PSG face Barcelona in the second leg of their last-eight Champions League tie on Tuesday and must overhaul a 3-1 deficit to progress to the semi-finals.</s>

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, fought a decade-long battle to change medical guidelines on cord clamping. She believed that clamping the cord within seconds of delivery was unnatural and potentially harmful. She gathered evidence with other medics and succeeded in getting the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to change its guidelines. NICE now states that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby. The cord should be clamped within five minutes, but left longer if the mother requests. The change means mothers get the chance to hold their babies for a moment while still connected to them. Despite resistance from colleagues and some doctors, Ms Burleigh felt a "moral duty" to challenge a practice that was not grounded in evidence.</s>

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to show no mercy if French peacekeepers are found guilty of sexually assaulting starving children in the Central African Republic. Fourteen soldiers have been accused of abusing children as young as nine in exchange for food, according to a French judicial source. The French defence ministry has denied covering up the scandal, and an investigation was launched last year. The UN employee who leaked the report has been suspended, and an unnamed staff member has been suspended for leaking the report. The violence in the Central African Republic has largely pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels who led the March 2013 coup against former leader Francois Bozize.</s>

The woman, identified as Aracely Meza, was arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission. The boy's mother reportedly knew Meza, but it is unclear if she is the child's mother. The incident took place at a home that also served as a church, and Meza used oils and prayed while trying to bring the boy back to life. The boy's death was reportedly due to either starvation or a fall from a chair, and emergency services were not called until four days later. The investigation is ongoing and involves both state and federal authorities.</s>

Tom Ballard, a skilled climber, plans to climb K2, the second highest mountain in the world, 20 years after his mother, Alison Hargreaves, died attempting the same feat. Alison Hargreaves, a renowned climber, was swept to her death in 1995 while descending K2 in 260mph winds. Tom was only six years old at the time. Despite the risks, Tom plans to follow in his mother's footsteps and climb K2. He believes it is his destiny to do so.</s>

UK Oil & Gas Investments claims to have discovered 100 billion barrels of oil in the Weald Basin, an area across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire, and Kent. The company believes this could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. However, industry experts remain skeptical, and one described the claims as "overly optimistic." The site at Horse Hill is believed to have the potential for "significant daily oil production." The oil is thought to be accessible, but fracking may be required to retrieve it. The discovery could create "many thousands" of jobs. The UK government owns the land under the homes in the area, meaning homeowners would not receive any profits from the oil found beneath them. The government would receive taxes on the oil extracted and may receive compensation from the oil company if they base their drilling site on the land.</s>

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA concluded that the first two years of culling had not demonstrated conclusively that ‘controlled shooting’ of free-running badgers could be effective and humane. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. The Environment Secretary promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but said the BVA’s ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting was ‘regrettable’. The Government's strategy includes cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife. The chief vet admitted the benefits of the cull might not be realised in Gloucestershire due to extensive unlawful protest and intimidation by anti-cull campaigners.</s>
